<DOC><DOCNO> AP900210-0153 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-10-90 0542EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-DigestBriefs     02-10 0688</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Digest Briefs,0715</SECOND><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Former President Reagan will give a videotapeddeposition for John Poindexter's trial in his first in-depthquestioning on the Iran-Contra affair since his two interviews withthe Tower Commission.   In those interviews conducted three years ago by theReagan-appointed commission, Reagan said he couldn't remember whenhe had approved arms sales to Iran.   Reagan on Friday consented to a videotaped deposition in whichPoindexter's lawyers will ask him 154 questions, plus follow-upquestions.   The subject areas will include Reagan's knowledge of OliverNorth's activities on behalf of the Contras and whether Reaganauthorized written responses to Congress relating to the Nicaraguanrebels. Poindexter now faces felony charges in connection withthose responses to Congress.</TEXT><DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Sixteen days before the presidentialelection, the leftist government honored a pledge and freed nearly1,000 Contra guerrillas and the last 39 jailed members of formerPresident Anastasio Somoza's National Guard.   President Daniel Ortega, who is running for re-election,proposed the pardon earlier this month. The pardon _ and therelease Friday _ deprived his major opponent, Violeta Barrios deChamorro, of a campaign issue for the Feb. 25 election.   The release was witnessed by diplomats, four Contra commanderswho have laid down their arms, international election observers andchurch and Red Cross representatives.   The Sandinista government made the most of the ceremony, takingseveral busloads of reporters to the Juan Navarro CentralPenitentiary, where the inmates stood in lines in front of theassembled dignitaries.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The resignation of a key official in PresidentBush's beleaguered savings-and-loan bureaucracy is worsening fearsthe government may be botching the selling of failed thrifts andtheir repossessed real estate.   Daniel P. Kearney, chief staff officer of the Resolution TrustCorp. Oversight Board, quit Friday after complaining the boardwasn't giving him the authority he needed to do his job.   The resignation is ``more evidence of the growing disarray inthe Bush administration,'' said Rep. Henry B. Gonzalez, D-Texas,chairman of the House Banking Committee. He predicted delay indealing with failed Sandamp;Ls would increase the taxpayer cost of thebailout.   Economist Paul Getman of Regional Financial Associates, aconsulting firm in Bala Cynwyd, Pa., said bureaucratic infightingis also heightening concern that a surplus of government-owned realestate will depress property prices in some areas.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The acquittal of reputed mob boss John Gotti oncharges he ordered the shooting of a union official brought cheersin court and a celebration in the Queens neighborhood where the``Dapper Don'' is king.   Gotti, whom authorities say has been America's No. 1 organizedcrime boss since December 1985, won his third victory overgovernment prosecutors Friday when a jury found him innocent ofassault and conspiracy.   His co-defendant, Anthony Guerrieri, was also acquitted.   Gotti's supporters applauded loudly as the verdict was read,provoking Acting Justice Edward McLaughlin to threaten them with 30days in jail if they didn't stop.   After leaving court, he arrived at a favorite hangout inManhattan's Little Italy and was cheered wildly by people waitingfor him on the street. Near another Gotti hangout, the Bergin Huntand Fish Club in the borough of Queens, residents decorated homesand stores with balloons and signs congratulating Gotti on hisacquittal.</TEXT><DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   NASA's Galileo spacecraft snappedphotographs of Venus today after zooming around the planet in a``celestial billiard shot'' that sent the robot explorer toward its1995 encounter with Jupiter.   ``We have clearly achieved the sole objective of going to Venus:a trajectory that will help us ultimately reach Jupiter,'' saidBill O'Neil, Galileo science and mission design manager at NASA'sJet Propulsion laboratory. ``All systems have been operatingperfectly.''   The 2.8-ton spacecraft made its closest approach to Venus at9:59 p.m. PST Friday, passing 10,028 miles above the furnace-likesurface of the second planet from the sun, O'Neil said.   Galileo's camera snapped pictures of the planet to study windand cloud patterns and search for lightning that might indicate thepresence of volcanoes erupting beneath the clouds.</TEXT></DOC>